Little wonder his press conferences were always well-attended by journalists, quacks and any layabout in town who could find his way to the venue.
Those were the days when the federation chief was guaranteed unfettered media coverage, even for the most mundane activities.
For the peanuts they received, some journalists swore allegiance to their supreme benefactor. These fellows would savagely attack any of their kind who dared write a ‘negative’ story about Nyamweya.
'Experience'
I speak from experience having once run into big trouble sometime in July 2013 for penning an opinion on these pages calling out my unprofessional colleagues for their dalliance with Nyamweya at the expense of objective news coverage.





At the time, word had it that some computer geek had hacked into Nyamweya’s mobile money transfer account and was about to unleash the names of sports journalists on his payroll.
For obvious reasons, the rumour threw many newsrooms into panic. Apparently, many palms had been repeatedly greased by the federation boss.
Mercifully, for the many worried souls, the much-dreaded dossier didn’t materialise.
But even then, I took a lot of flak from my colleagues for my well-intended piece. I was branded a spoilsport. Some even went around saying that I was merely 'bitter' because I had been denied an opportunity to dip my fingers into the honey jar. Preposterous and laughable allegations!



