Emboldened by the sway he held over sports journalists, Nyamweya would at times go overboard in his efforts to suppress ‘negative’ coverage. This he was able to do with the help of snitches who held brief for him in nearly all mainstream newsrooms.
There was one particularly hilarious incident late one evening when a certain sports sub editor, who was furiously banging away copy to beat the fast-approaching deadline, got an unexpected phone call from Nyamweya.
The federation boss wanted to know why the sub editor was hellbent on publishing a negative story about him. One of Nyamweya’s hatchet men in the newsrooms had leaked the following day's big story. Now he wanted to have the story killed.
Such was the working relationship between the federation and Kenyan journalists back then.
But times have changed. So too has the face and sound of the federation. The ‘good old days’ are far behind us. Long gone is the charitable Nyamweya, his place taken by the malevolent Nick Mwendwa.
Unlike Nyamweya, Mwendwa is not a man given to dolling journalists with freebies. Handouts at press conferences are thankfully now a thing of the past.
Let me state here that no Kenyan sports journalist worth his salt needs handouts from Mwendwa, or any sports administrator for that matter.



